ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
(a) Experimental setup of the oven experiments. The ambient temperature (Ta
                     ), the middle (Tm
                     ) and surface (Ts
                     ) temperature of the cells are measured using thermocouples with an error of ± 1℃. The voltage of a cell is measured using high-temperature resistant wires connecting with a battery cycler. (b) Photographs of the different numbers of cells. Bi numbers are calculated based on the parameters in work [33].

ce:section.ce:para:
The experiments were conducted in a mechanically ventilated oven to quantify the critical minimum ambient temperature for self-heating ignition of cells, based on the procedure in the British Standards EN 15188:2007. The numbers of cells of 1, 2 and 4 were used. Fig. 1
                         shows the overall experimental setup. Cells were closely stacked together placing at the center of a metal mesh cage, which was used to prevent the fires and projectiles from destroying the oven. The fine wires were used around cells to fix the shape of stacks and keep cells in contact with each other. Three thermocouples were employed to measure the surface temperature of the middle cell (Tm
                        ), the surface temperature of the outmost cell (Ts
                        ), and the ambient temperature (Ta
                        ). The voltage of a cell is monitored using high-temperature resistant wires connecting with a battery cycler. The mass lost is the difference between the mass of a fresh cell and its mass after an experiment.
